    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.25"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">25</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115 Street
                        New York City
                        July 15th, 29
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>I wrote you yesterday in appreciation of your poems and letter. Today I am copying the following (though I think I have sent the lines to you) because of the St. Louis association, and becasue of the very remarkable testament the script is.</p>
                
                <p>I first heard of Mrs. Curran through Mr. Reedy, who had a great regard for her. This in 1917. There was no possible connection in her knowing anythign of me, and when I met her On April 30, 1925, <hi rend="underline">under absolute test conditions</hi>, <add>(</add>for she had no idea who I was<add>)</add> she gave me the following<add>,</add> <hi rend="underline">instantly</hi> on request. (To me this has been most arresting<add>,</add> that the poem came on May Eve, beause of my own ancestral connection with that great Feast of the Druids):</p>
                
                    <lg>
                        <l>To become an urn,</l>
                        <l>To pour forth freely a stuff,</l>
                        <l>The holy stuff which be lended to thy hand,</l>
                        <l>Poured by that sacred Hand</l>
                        <l>Which ne'er hath erred.</l>
                        <l>To become quickened of this touch,</l>
                        <l>Tranquil, yea, as an amazed child</l>
                        <l>Before Knowledge --not before wisdom,</l>
                        <l>Which is the garment of Knowledge--</l>
                        <l>But before a <hi rend="caps">CERTAIN KNOWLEDGE</hi>.</l>
                        <l>To become quickened in thy in-man</l>
                        <l>With an itch for surety,</l>
                        <l>And be-baffled by the thing</l>
                        <l>Which confronts thee!</l>
                        <l>This be nae fair fight, eh?</l>
                        <l>Yet I say me,</l>
                        <l>To become a crucible for such an potent stuff</l>
                        <l>I<del/><add>s</add> to become a Holy Vessel.</l>
                        <l>And what then shall earth take up--</l>
                        <l>The Holy Vessel, and consume?</l>
                        <l>Or shall it for to break it?</l>
                        <l>I say me, it shall be drunk,</l>
                        <l>And drunk thirstily.</l>
                    </lg>
                
                <p>As I was leaving, Mrs. <hi rend="caps">C.</hi> said, "Patience has something more for you. But one greater than she is speaking through her."</p>
                
                    <lg>
                        <l>Behold I dip mine sword within a holy red,</l>
                        <l>And its tip is flamed,</l>
                        <l>And I have placed it within thine hand.</l>
                    </lg>
                
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>-----------</ab>
                
                <p>There was no talk of my work nor of my experiences during our conversation. Mrs. <hi rend="caps">C.</hi> had absolutely no knowledge of me. If you ever wish to use the above se<del><unclear>ap</unclear></del><add>pa</add>rately --as a substantiation of Mrs. <hi rend="caps">C.</hi> if she ever needs it-- please fe<del>l</del><add>e</add>l free to do so. But not in connection with your own estimate: I want that strong and clear interpretation mixed with no thought but your own.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed><unclear>Tom</unclear></signed>
                </closer>
                    
            </div1>
